Exercise 1: Multilevel modeling

Consider the dataset nyc_arrests.txt related to the police stops (you find the dataset in the Exam section in the Moodle page): for further details, see G& H book, Chapter 15, and lecture notes about hierarchical models, slides 123128.

Fit the model (24) in the notes from a Bayesian and a frequentist point of view, using rstanarm/rstan and lme4 packages.

Dataset loading and data exploration

First, lets load the data and take a look at it.

data <- read.table("datasets/nyc_arrests.txt", header = TRUE, sep = " ", skip = 6) # the first 5 written lines are comments about the dataset

# adding a small value to the zero values of past.arrests to avoid numerical errors
data$past.arrests <- data$past.arrests + 0.0001
# Correct the zero values for numerical errors <---- da capire. Se metto 0 nella log likelihod mi da errore <- questa parte la posso riscrivere pi avanti

  1. stops: Number of police stops recorded;

  2. pop: Population size in the precinct;

  3. past.arrests: Measure of past arrests;

  4. precinct: Precinct number, ranging from 1 to 75;

  5. eth: Ethnicity type: 1 for Black, 2 for Hispanic and 3 for White;

  6. crime: Crime type: 1 for Violent crimes, 2 for Weapons crimes, 3 for Property crimes and 4 for Drug crimes.

Variables distributions:

For each of the 4 crime, we can check the Stops distributions:

  • grouped by precinct:

  • grouped by ethnicity:

From this plots we may infer that the number of stops is higher in some precint, depending on the crime type, and that there may be some higher stop rates for Black and Hispanic, compared to White.

Well take this info into account and fit model (24). A Poisson multilevel model that estimates the number of stops, while considering the variations among precincts and ethnic groups.

Model (24): \[y_{ep} \sim \text{Poisson} \left( \frac{15}{12} u_{ep} e^{\mu + \alpha_e + \beta_p + \epsilon_{ep}} \right)\] \[\alpha_e \sim N(0, \sigma^2_{\alpha}) \\ \beta_p \sim N(0, \sigma^2_{\beta}) \\ \epsilon_{ep} \sim N(0, \sigma^2_{\epsilon})\]

where:

  • \(y_{ep}\) corresponds to stops: the number of stops in the precinct for the ethnicity relative to the crime;
  • \(u_{ep}\) corresponds to past.arrests: the number of past arrests in the precinct p for the ethnicity e;
  • \(u\) corresponds to the fixed effect: the intercept at the individual level;
  • \(\alpha_e\) and \(\beta_p\) correspond to the ethnic and precinct random effects, respectively;
  • \(\epsilon_{ep}\) corresponds to the error term to account for overdispersion.

Models Fitting:

# Define the models lists to store the models
fr_models <- list()
ba_models <- list()

# Fit the models for each crime
for (i in 1:4){ 
cat("\nFitting the Frequentist model for crime ", i, "\n")
# Fit the frequentist model using glmer
fr_models[[i]] <- glmer(stops ~ 1 + (1|eth) + (1|precinct) + (1|eth:precinct),
                    offset = log((15/12) * past.arrests),
                    data = data,
                    subset = (crime == i),
                    family = poisson())

cat("\nFitting the Bayesian model for crime ", i, "\n")
# Fit the bayesian model using stan_glmer
ba_models[[i]] <- stan_glmer(stops ~ 1 + (1|eth) + (1|precinct) + (1|eth:precinct),
                    offset = log((15/12) * past.arrests),
                    data = data,
                    subset = (crime == i),
                    prior = normal(),
                    family = poisson(),
                    seed = 42)
}

Fit directly a negative binomial model using rstanarm/rstan and compare it with the previous estimates.

To address overdispersion as an alternative to the \(\epsilon_{ep}\) term in the poisson model, we can fit a negative binomial model. Following a similar approach as before, we will use rstanarm to fit this model and compare it with the previous estimates:

nb_models <- list()
for (i in 1:4){
cat("Fitting the Negative Binomial model for crime ", i,"\n")
nb_models[[i]] <- stan_glmer(stops ~ 1 + (1|eth) + (1|precinct),
                             offset = log((15/12) * past.arrests),
                             data = data,
                             subset = (crime == i),
                             prior = normal(),
                             family = neg_binomial_2(),
                             seed = 42)
}

Compare models in terms of predictive information criteria.

To compare the models, we can use the Leave-One-Out Cross-Validation (LOOIC), available via the loo package. Models with lower LOOIC values generally exhibit better predictive accuracy on unseen data.

Divide the dataset in training/test and make some predictions.

Well divide the dataset in training and test set, fit the models on train_data (80% of the data) and make some predictions on test_data (20% of the data).

First, well split the data into training and testing sets:

# Set the seed for reproducibility
set.seed(42)
train_indices <- sample(seq_len(nrow(data)), size = 0.8 * nrow(data))
# Create training and testing sets
train_data <- data[train_indices, ]
test_data <- data[-train_indices, ]

Then, we can train the Poisson and the Negative Binomil models on the training set:

# Fit the models on the training set
bayesian_models_train <- list()
nb_models_train <- list()
for (i in 1:4){
  cat("\nFitting the Bayesian model for crime ", i, " on the training set\n")
  bayesian_models_train[[i]] <- stan_glmer(stops ~ 1 + (1|eth) + (1|precinct) + (1|eth:precinct),
                                          offset = log((15/12) * past.arrests),
                                          data = train_data,
                                          subset = (crime == i),
                                          prior = normal(),
                                          family = poisson(),
                                          seed = 42)
  cat("\nFitting the Negative Binomial model for crime ", i, " on the training set\n")
  nb_models_train[[i]] <- stan_glmer(stops ~ 1 + (1|eth) + (1|precinct),
                                    offset = log((15/12) * past.arrests),
                                    data = train_data,
                                    subset = (crime == i),
                                    prior = normal(),
                                    family = neg_binomial_2(),
                                    seed = 42)
}

Finally we can make some predictions on the test set and evaluate the models:

Once the predictions are made, we can evaluate them using the RMSE and the MAE metrics:

## Overall Results: 
## Poisson Model - MAE: 163.6833
## 
## Poisson Model - RMSE: 301.7796
## 
## Negative Binomial Model - MAE: 209.2333
## 
## Negative Binomial Model - RMSE: 400.1642

From these results we may be tempted to say that the Poisson model is better than the Negative Binomial model.

However, the predictions of the models are highly dependent on the seed used (123 in this case). Hence, before deriving any conclusion, well now compare the MAE and RMSE values as the seed changes. Well use seeds from 1 to 200, plot the MAE and RMSE values and get an overall mean values for these metrics. This could give us some higher quality insights on the models performances.

## Mean values of these metrics for the Poisson model over the first 20 seeds: 
##  - MAE:  201.2911 
##  - RMSE:  377.706
## 
## Mean values of these metrics for the Negative Binomial model over the first 20 seeds: 
##  - MAE:  200.7041 
##  - RMSE:  387.5385

From the plots we can see that both models have highly variable performances. However, the average the performances of the Poisson model are superior.

Nonetheless, is evident how both models exhibit limitations in achieving highly accurate predictions. This suggests a need for further investigation and exploration of alternative models that may provide improved fit.

Extend the model: write a modeling extension (fit is not required) where a further continuous covariate income_ethnicity, expressing an average income for the ethnicity e in New-York City, is available. (Hint: there is not a unique way to incorporate it). Finally, discuss the eventual sign of the estimated coefficient from a socio-political perspective.

An alternative model, that incorporates the continuous covariate \(\text{income}_e\), could be:

  • Poisson model: \[y_{ep} \sim \text{Poisson} \left( \frac{15}{12} u_{ep} e^{\mu + \alpha_e + \beta_p + \epsilon_{ep} + \gamma_e \cdot \text{income}_e} \right) \\ \alpha_e \sim N(0, \sigma^2_{\alpha}) \\ \beta_p \sim N(0, \sigma^2_{\beta}) \\ \epsilon_{ep} \sim N(0, \sigma^2_{\epsilon}) \\ \gamma_e \sim N(0, \sigma^2_{\gamma}) \\\]

  • Negative Binomial Model: \[y_{ep} \sim \text{NB} \left( \frac{15}{12} u_{ep} e^{\mu + \alpha_e + \beta_p + \gamma_e \cdot \text{income}_e}, \omega_{ep} \right) \\ \alpha_e \sim N(0, \sigma^2_{\alpha}) \\ \beta_p \sim N(0, \sigma^2_{\beta}) \\ \gamma_e \sim N(0, \sigma^2_{\gamma}) \\\]

where \(\omega_{ep}\) is the overdispersione parameter of the NB model.

From a socio-political standpoint, we might anticipate that the estimated number of stops would increase as average income decreases. This would be the case with a positive \(\gamma_e\). It could be reasonable to infer that lower-income communities may experience higher rates of police stops, possibly due to the correlation between lower income and higher crime rates. Conversely, as the income of an ethnic group increases, the number of police stops might decrease.
